{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487141"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:59:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:59:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"264"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/264"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.01,0.11,0.16,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/264"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75118"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"6427"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31253"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four hour history of severe right-sided colicky abdominal pain associated with vomiting. He is otherwise well and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/70mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min and temperature 36.4C. There is some tenderness on palpation of the right flank. Bedside urinalysis returns positive for blood (++) but is otherwise normal. Bloods are unremarkable. Abdominal ultrasound is initially performed and shows mild right-sided hydronephrosis.\u00a0A non-contrast CT scan subsequently shows a 3mm stone at the vesico-ureteric junction with mild upstream hydroureteronephrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Percutaneous nephrostomy","Intravenous antibiotics","Extracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy","Cystoscopy and ureteric stent insertion","Analgesia and wait for spontaneous passage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor small distal ureteric stones in a patient who does not demonstrate evidence of infection the most appropriate management is often \u003Cstrong\u003Esupportive care and trial of spontaneous passage\u003C/strong\u003E. Upstream hydroureteronephrosis is an expected finding, as renal colic only occurs when the stone becomes impacted - this in itself is not an indication for surgical intervention. In this case the patient has a relatively short history and the stone has already reached the vesico-ureteric junction and it will almost certainly pass spontaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary factor determining likelihood of spontaneous passage is stone size. Stones of 4.2 mm diameter or less have a roughly 70% chance of passing, with progressive increase in likelihood for every millimeter smaller. Stones of 6.5 mm diameter or greater will almost certainly need some form of intervention. However, stone position will also influence the decision to treat, as although a smaller proximal stone may eventually pass, the patient may be intolerably symptomatic while it is en route.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegardless of size, interventional treatment is indicated if features of either infection with obstruction or total renal obstruction (i.e. single kidney, bilateral stones, anuria) are present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Stones 4.2 mm and under are more likely than not to pass spontaneously and supportive care may be all that is required"],"references":["Urolithiasis - Ten things every general practitioner should know. Sewell J, Katz DJ, Shoshany O, Love C. Aust Fam Physician. 2017 Sep;46(9):648-652.","Thia I, Saluja M. An update on management of renal colic. Aust J Gen Pract. 2021 Jul;50(7):445-449.","Jendeberg J, Geijer H, Alhamari M et al. Prediction of spontaneous ureteral stone passage: Automated 3D-measurements perform equal to radiologists, and linear measurements equal to volumetric. Eur Radiol 2018; 28:2474-83."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75118"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"264"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75118"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T19:57:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-15T19:57:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"264"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91447"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":""